nodej stream ke bare me simple language me text 200-300 mb ka likho

Node.js me Streams ka simple matlab hai: "Data ko chhote-chhote tukdo (chunks) me continuous flow karwana, bina puri file ko ek saath memory me load kiye."

Isko ek simple real-life example se samajhte hain. Jab aap YouTube par koi video dekhte hain, toh kya puri 1 GB ki video pehle download hoti hai? Nahi. Video ke chhote-chhote parts download hote rehte hain aur play hote rehte hain. Isi ko streaming kehte hain.

Agar aapko Node.js me 200-300 MB ya usse badi file par kaam karna hai, toh Streams aapke liye sabse best aur efficient tarika hain.

Streams Kyun Zaroori Hain? (The Problem vs. Solution)
Maan lo aapke paas 300 MB ki ek text file hai aur aap use padhna (read) chahte hain.

Bina Stream ke (Fs.readFile): Node.js pehle us puri 300 MB ki file ko uthaakar aapki RAM (buffer memory) me daalega, aur phir aapko content dikhayega. Agar file 2 GB ki hui, toh aapka server crash ho sakta hai (Out of Memory Error).

Stream ke saath (Fs.createReadStream): Node.js file ko 64 KB (default size) ke chhote-chhote chunks me todega. Ek chunk read hoga, process hoga, aur memory se saaf ho jayega. Phir dusra chunk aayega. Isse aapki RAM par bilkul load nahi padta—chahe file 300 MB ki ho ya 30 GB ki!

Node.js me Streams ke Types
Streams majorly 4 types ki hoti hain:

Readable Stream: Jahan se data ko read (padha) jata hai. (Example: fs.createReadStream())

Writable Stream: Jahan data ko write (likha) jata hai. (Example: fs.createWriteStream())

Duplex Stream: Jo Read aur Write dono kaam ek saath kar sakti hai. (Example: Network sockets net.Socket)

Transform Stream: Yeh ek special Duplex stream hai jo data ko read karte-karte modify (change) bhi kar sakti hai. (Example: File ko compress/zip karna using zlib)

Code Example: 300 MB ki File ko Handle Karna
Agar aapko 300 MB ki file ko read karke kisi dusri jagah write karna hai, toh aap streams ka use aise karenge:

JavaScript
const fs = require('fs');

// 1. Readable stream banayein (300 MB ki file read karne ke liye)
const readStream = fs.createReadStream('large_input_file.txt', { encoding: 'utf-8' });

// 2. Writable stream banayein (Nayi file me data write karne ke liye)
const writeStream = fs.createWriteStream('output_file.txt');

// 3. 'data' event: Jaise hi data ka ek chhota chunk ready hoga, yeh trigger hoga
readStream.on('data', (chunk) => {
    console.log("--- Ek naya chunk aaya! ---");
    writeStream.write(chunk); // Chunk ko nayi file me write kar rahe hain
});

// 4. 'end' event: Jab puri 300 MB file read ho jayegi
readStream.on('end', () => {
    console.log("Puri file successfully process ho gayi hai!");
});
Pro-Tip: .pipe() ka jadu
Upar diye gaye code ko likhne ka ek aur aasan aur advanced tarika hai—Pipe. Yeh data ko readable stream se uthaakar apne aap writable stream me daal deta hai aur background me data flow (backpressure) ko bhi khud manage karta hai.

JavaScript
// Sirf 1 line me 300 MB file copy:
readStream.pipe(writeStream);
Streams ke Fayde (Benefits)
Memory Efficiency: RAM ka sahi upyog hota hai. 300 MB ki file ko process karne ke liye sirf kuch KB memory chahiye hoti hai.

Time Efficiency: Aapko puri file read hone ka wait nahi karna padta. Jaise hi pehla chunk milta hai, processing shuru ho jati hai.

Short me kahein toh, Streams badhe data (badi files ya network requests) ko smart tarike se kam memory me handle karne ka zariya hain.

nahi ek file .txt banana hai jisme tumhe kam se kam 2000 line likhni hai simple exglish me

